{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d147c9c9-59f5-4ddf-bbdc-b3cd3353d361","content":"With **MSTest.Sdk 3.8.0**, Microsoft.Testing.Platform is already the **default** runner. You just need one change:\n\n**In your project file**, remove (or delete) the VSTest opt-in:\n\n```xml\n<!-- Remove this line -->\n<UseVSTest>true</UseVSTest>\n```\n\nThat's it — the SDK defaults to Microsoft.Testing.Platform when `UseVSTest` is absent or `false`.\n\n### Things to be aware of after switching\n\n| Area | Notes |\n|---|---|\n| **`dotnet test`** | Still works; it auto-detects the new platform. |\n| **Direct execution** | You can now also run tests via the built executable: `./YourTests --list-tests`, `./YourTests --filter \"Name=Foo\"`. |\n| **`.runsettings`** | Still supported, but some VSTest-only knobs (e.g. `<RunConfiguration><TestAdaptersPaths>`) no longer apply. |\n| **VSTest adapters** | Third-party VSTest adapters won't load. Look for Microsoft.Testing.Platform equivalents (e.g., replace coverlet VSTest collector with `--coverage` or a platform extension). |\n| **CI / TRX output** | Add `<OutputType>trx</OutputType>` or pass `--results-directory` + `--report-trx` if your CI relies on TRX files. |","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c042c044-4d50-4f50-a79b-55e1c5f6b363","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating from VSTest to Microsoft.Testing.Platform in their MSTest project that uses MSTest.Sdk/3.8.0. This is a general knowledge question about .NET testing configuration - I don't need to explore any codebase for this.\n\nLet me provide a concise answer based on my knowledge of MSTest.Sdk and Microsoft.Testing.Platform.\n\nWhen using MSTest.Sdk, the migration from VSTest to Microsoft.Testing.Platform is straightforward:\n\n1. Remove `<UseVSTest>true</UseVSTest>` from the project file (or set it to `false`). Starting with MSTest.Sdk 3.x, Microsoft.Testing.Platform is the default runner.\n\n\n2. Beyond that, the SDK handles most of the transition automatically, though I should note that CLI commands like `dotnet test` still work, some VSTest-specific configurations in `.runsettings` files might need tweaking, and any custom extensions or adapters could behave differently with the new platform.","outputTokens":614},"id":"99b07a69-b624-49dd-a107-369336011eda","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:44:48.928Z","parentId":"2aa0601c-f4a4-4eaa-b175-5a6aa97263a1"}
